 \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction of C1 oxoanion species on reduced iron surfaces yields methanal after dehydration/protonation steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduced iron and magnetite promote hydrogenation of oxidized carbon species under hydrothermal conditions; use of formaldehyde as a transferable C1 intermediate is consistent with hydrothermal-to-surface coupling although exact yields remain environment dependent (He et al., 2010; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal vent or subseafloor setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2-derived reduced C1 units undergo surface carbon-carbon coupling and partial reduction to give a C2 aldehyde, glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type and related hydrothermal catalytic processes on iron minerals can generate low-molecular-weight oxygenates including aldehydes; glycolaldehyde is a plausible transferable sugar precursor feeding surface chemistry (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent redox and pH gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation and carbon-carbon bond formation produce an \u03b1-keto acid analogous to reductive acetyl-CoA/reductive TCA chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a central \u03b1-keto acid in prebiotic protometabolism and has been discussed as a plausible hydrothermal product of Fe-S mediated carbon fixation networks, though specific routes remain partly model-driven (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic NH3-bearing vent fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia on mineral surfaces followed by reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids under hydrothermal mineral catalysis is a standard prebiotic route to amino acids and links carbon fixation chemistry to amino acid inventories (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical generation of HCN from reduced C1 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pool, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven photocatalytic oxidation-reduction and dehydration of reduced C1/N species yields nitrile functionality, furnishing HCN as a reactive nitrogen-carbon hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is central to surface prebiotic synthesis networks; TiO2-assisted UV photochemistry and sulfur-assisted cyanide generation are used here as a plausible coupling of reduced hydrothermal feedstocks to cyanosulfidic surface chemistry (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN hydration to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure with intermittent drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN is hydrated in the presence of mineral surfaces to formamide, a versatile precursor pool for further N-C chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide chemistry is strongly represented in prebiotic synthesis scenarios and can arise from cyanide hydrolysis/hydration under surface conditions; mineral surfaces enhance concentration and subsequent transformations (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface partial hydrolysis/reduction of HCN to methanimine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-driven redox cycling, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated nitrile chemistry followed by proton-coupled reduction furnishes the imine methanimine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Methanimine is a recognized intermediate in prebiotic amino acid chemistry and can bridge cyanide chemistry to amino nitriles; this step is plausible though less directly constrained than Strecker addition itself (Danger et al., 2012; Woon, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool with concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine that is attacked by cyanide to give aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is among the most established prebiotic routes to amino acid precursors. For glycine specifically, formaldehyde plus NH3 and HCN gives aminoacetonitrile as the direct nitrile precursor (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aminoacetonitrile formation from methanimine and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"condensing shallow-pool environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to methanimine yields the aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Amino nitriles can form by direct cyanide addition to imines; this provides a second convergent route to aminoacetonitrile from the HCN hub and is chemically aligned with Strecker-type logic (Danger et al., 2012; Bernstein et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated pool; borate stabilizes carbonyl species\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox oxidation of the aldehyde/alcohol functionality of glycolaldehyde gives the \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a plausible oxidation product of simple aldehydes in surface settings and is a useful hub linking sugar chemistry to amino acid chemistry; borate can stabilize reactive carbonyl intermediates in these networks (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ricardo et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidative fragmentation of pyruvate to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation/decarboxylative rearrangement of pyruvate furnishes glyoxylate under surface redox cycling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate and glyoxylate are interconvertible within abiotic carbonyl networks, and pyruvate photochemistry provides a second route into the glyoxylate hub, linking hydrothermal \u03b1-keto acid production to surface amino acid synthesis (Muchowska et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface borate-stabilized formose step to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type carbon-carbon bond formation between reduced carbonyl compounds yields glyceraldehyde, stabilized against runaway formose degradation by borate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Borate-assisted sugar chemistry is a central strategy for stabilizing triose products in prebiotic surface environments, and glyceraldehyde acts as a branching point into oxidation and retro-aldol chemistry (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface retro-aldol/oxidative conversion of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure with intermittent drying\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photooxidative fragmentation of the triose yields a C2 \u03b1-keto acid pool including glyoxylate while regenerating formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dynamic carbonyl exchange in surface sugar chemistry allows feedback between triose and C1/C2 pools, strengthening network connectivity; this step is plausible but partly network-completion oriented (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; speculative integration).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN dimerization to cyanogen\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photochemistry in concentrated cyanide pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical radical coupling/oxidative dimerization of cyanide gives cyanogen.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization and related cyanide coupling reactions are classical features of prebiotic cyanide chemistry, and cyanogen-like species can feed further aminonitrile derivatization (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Sanchez et al., 1967).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface conversion of cyanogen and ammonia to aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing, cyanide-rich pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated dinitrile chemistry followed by ammonolysis and reduction gives aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a more speculative but chemically motivated alternative route to the glycine aminonitrile hub from cyanide oligomer chemistry, included to create pathway redundancy around aminoacetonitrile (speculative integration based on cyanide oligomer literature: Ferris & Orgel, 1966).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formamide-cyanide route to aminoacetonitrile derivative\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted concentration in drying pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide-derived amidation/cyanation chemistry yields an activated glycine-related nitrile-amide intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide networks can access nitrile-containing intermediates relevant to amino acid synthesis; this step is included as a plausible bridge from HCN hydration chemistry to glycine precursors though exact structure/yield is less established (Saladino et al., 2012; speculative integration).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolytic conversion of activated glycine nitrile-amide to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry hydrolysis in mineral-rich pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile and amide hydrolysis furnishes the amino acid carboxylate/ammonium pair identified as glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Mineral-assisted hydrolysis of aminonitrile-type precursors to amino acids is broadly accepted in prebiotic chemistry and provides a direct route from activated nitrile-amide pools to glycine (Peltzer et al., 1984; Danger et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles promote nitrile hydration and completion to amino acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide and acid stages to yield glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile is the canonical completion step of Strecker chemistry to glycine and is strongly supported in prebiotic amino acid synthesis literature (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing pool with NH3 and dissolved H2 equivalents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate forms an imine with ammonia followed by reduction to the \u03b1-amino acid glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is a direct and metabolically relevant path to amino acids. Glyoxylate is the C2 analogue that gives glycine, providing a route independent of Strecker chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2017; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic transamination of glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pool or mineral interface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to glyoxylate generates glycine and regenerates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination is a key network-connecting process that links hydrothermally generated alanine and pyruvate to glycine synthesis through glyoxylate, creating a plausible proto-metabolic loop even if uncatalyzed rates are modest (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical decarboxylation/oxidative shortening of pyruvate to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling; speculative multi-step net conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Net conversion invokes pyruvate decarboxylation to a C2 carbonyl followed by amination and oxidation-state adjustment to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a speculative net step included to represent a proto-metabolic shortening route from pyruvate to glycine in geothermal pools. It is less directly evidenced than Strecker or glyoxylate amination routes but helps capture plausible network flexibility around \u03b1-keto acid chemistry (speculative integration informed by protometabolic carbonyl chemistry: Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Strecker route from hydrothermal formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates formate and formaldehyde, which feed a surface Strecker synthesis to aminoacetonitrile followed by hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct formaldehyde Strecker without explicit HCN regeneration loop\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde enters the surface environment and directly undergoes Strecker synthesis with pre-existing HCN and ammonia, then hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Methanimine-mediated aminonitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanide is reduced to methanimine, which captures cyanide to form aminoacetonitrile and then hydrolyzes to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanogen branch to aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN dimerizes to cyanogen, which in a reducing ammoniacal pool yields aminoacetonitrile, then glycine by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-derived nitrile-amide route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN hydrates to formamide, then enters a cyanation route to an activated glycine-related nitrile-amide intermediate that hydrolyzes to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to surface glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde is transferred to the surface, photooxidized to glyoxylate, then reductively aminated to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to surface glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate generated hydrothermally is photochemically converted to glyoxylate in surface pools and then aminated to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized sugar route to glyoxylate and glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde feed surface borate-stabilized sugar chemistry to glyceraldehyde, which fragments oxidatively to glyoxylate and then gives glycine by reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal alanine to biochemical transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is aminated to alanine; surface or hydrothermal pyruvate also supplies glyoxylate, and biochemical transamination between alanine and glyoxylate yields glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-metabolic shortening of pyruvate to glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate enters a biochemical/prebiotic geothermal pool where net decarboxylative and aminating transformations furnish glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glycine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets glycine through ten interconnected prebiotic routes spanning hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface cyanide and carbonyl chemistry, and biochemical/prebiotic conversion steps. The network is built around hub intermediates shared across environments: carbon dioxide, formate, formaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide, glyoxylate, and glycine itself. Hydrothermal reactions generate reduced C1-C3 feedstocks such as formate, acetate, pyruvate, formaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals. Surface environments use these feedstocks in HCN photochemistry, Strecker-type synthesis, formose/aldol chemistry, and oxidation to glyoxylate. Biochemical/prebiotic steps connect \u03b1-keto acid and aminonitrile chemistry to the final amino acid pool and peptide-forming context. The resulting bipartite graph provides multiple convergent and redundant routes to glycine while preserving full network connectivity and cross-environment transfer.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H3NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H2N2", "iupac_name": "ethanedinitrile", "common_name": "cyanogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2N2/c3-1-2-4", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H2N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h2H2,4H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "methanimine", "common_name": "methanimine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3N/c1-2/h1H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H4N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-2-oxoacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycinenitrile amide / aminocyanoformamide analogue", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of carbon dioxide to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated CO2 adsorption and stepwise two-electron reduction by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.", "reasoning": "Fe-S minerals are widely invoked as catalysts for CO2 reduction under alkaline hydrothermal conditions, making formate a key reduced C1 feedstock and network hub in iron-sulfur world chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal conversion of formate to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of C1 oxoanion species on reduced iron surfaces yields methanal after dehydration/protonation steps.", "reasoning": "Reduced iron and magnetite promote hydrogenation of oxidized carbon species under hydrothermal conditions; use of formaldehyde as a transferable C1 intermediate is consistent with hydrothermal-to-surface coupling although exact yields remain environment dependent (He et al., 2010; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal vent or subseafloor setting"}, "mechanism": "CO2-derived reduced C1 units undergo surface carbon-carbon coupling and partial reduction to give a C2 aldehyde, glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type and related hydrothermal catalytic processes on iron minerals can generate low-molecular-weight oxygenates including aldehydes; glycolaldehyde is a plausible transferable sugar precursor feeding surface chemistry (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent redox and pH gradients"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation and carbon-carbon bond formation produce an \u03b1-keto acid analogous to reductive acetyl-CoA/reductive TCA chemistry.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a central \u03b1-keto acid in prebiotic protometabolism and has been discussed as a plausible hydrothermal product of Fe-S mediated carbon fixation networks, though specific routes remain partly model-driven (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic NH3-bearing vent fluids"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia on mineral surfaces followed by reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids under hydrothermal mineral catalysis is a standard prebiotic route to amino acids and links carbon fixation chemistry to amino acid inventories (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Muchowska et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface photochemical generation of HCN from reduced C1 feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pool, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven photocatalytic oxidation-reduction and dehydration of reduced C1/N species yields nitrile functionality, furnishing HCN as a reactive nitrogen-carbon hub.", "reasoning": "HCN is central to surface prebiotic synthesis networks; TiO2-assisted UV photochemistry and sulfur-assisted cyanide generation are used here as a plausible coupling of reduced hydrothermal feedstocks to cyanosulfidic surface chemistry (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface HCN hydration to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure with intermittent drying"}, "mechanism": "HCN is hydrated in the presence of mineral surfaces to formamide, a versatile precursor pool for further N-C chemistry.", "reasoning": "Formamide chemistry is strongly represented in prebiotic synthesis scenarios and can arise from cyanide hydrolysis/hydration under surface conditions; mineral surfaces enhance concentration and subsequent transformations (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface partial hydrolysis/reduction of HCN to methanimine", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven redox cycling, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Activated nitrile chemistry followed by proton-coupled reduction furnishes the imine methanimine.", "reasoning": "Methanimine is a recognized intermediate in prebiotic amino acid chemistry and can bridge cyanide chemistry to amino nitriles; this step is plausible though less directly constrained than Strecker addition itself (Danger et al., 2012; Woon, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool with concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine that is attacked by cyanide to give aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is among the most established prebiotic routes to amino acid precursors. For glycine specifically, formaldehyde plus NH3 and HCN gives aminoacetonitrile as the direct nitrile precursor (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface aminoacetonitrile formation from methanimine and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "condensing shallow-pool environment"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to methanimine yields the aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "Amino nitriles can form by direct cyanide addition to imines; this provides a second convergent route to aminoacetonitrile from the HCN hub and is chemically aligned with Strecker-type logic (Danger et al., 2012; Bernstein et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated pool; borate stabilizes carbonyl species"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox oxidation of the aldehyde/alcohol functionality of glycolaldehyde gives the \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a plausible oxidation product of simple aldehydes in surface settings and is a useful hub linking sugar chemistry to amino acid chemistry; borate can stabilize reactive carbonyl intermediates in these networks (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ricardo et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface oxidative fragmentation of pyruvate to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation/decarboxylative rearrangement of pyruvate furnishes glyoxylate under surface redox cycling.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate and glyoxylate are interconvertible within abiotic carbonyl networks, and pyruvate photochemistry provides a second route into the glyoxylate hub, linking hydrothermal \u03b1-keto acid production to surface amino acid synthesis (Muchowska et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Surface borate-stabilized formose step to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldol-type carbon-carbon bond formation between reduced carbonyl compounds yields glyceraldehyde, stabilized against runaway formose degradation by borate.", "reasoning": "Borate-assisted sugar chemistry is a central strategy for stabilizing triose products in prebiotic surface environments, and glyceraldehyde acts as a branching point into oxidation and retro-aldol chemistry (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Surface retro-aldol/oxidative conversion of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure with intermittent drying"}, "mechanism": "Photooxidative fragmentation of the triose yields a C2 \u03b1-keto acid pool including glyoxylate while regenerating formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Dynamic carbonyl exchange in surface sugar chemistry allows feedback between triose and C1/C2 pools, strengthening network connectivity; this step is plausible but partly network-completion oriented (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; speculative integration)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Surface HCN dimerization to cyanogen", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photochemistry in concentrated cyanide pools"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical radical coupling/oxidative dimerization of cyanide gives cyanogen.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomerization and related cyanide coupling reactions are classical features of prebiotic cyanide chemistry, and cyanogen-like species can feed further aminonitrile derivatization (Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Sanchez et al., 1967)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Surface conversion of cyanogen and ammonia to aminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing, cyanide-rich pool"}, "mechanism": "Activated dinitrile chemistry followed by ammonolysis and reduction gives aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is a more speculative but chemically motivated alternative route to the glycine aminonitrile hub from cyanide oligomer chemistry, included to create pathway redundancy around aminoacetonitrile (speculative integration based on cyanide oligomer literature: Ferris & Orgel, 1966)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Surface formamide-cyanide route to aminoacetonitrile derivative", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-assisted concentration in drying pools"}, "mechanism": "Formamide-derived amidation/cyanation chemistry yields an activated glycine-related nitrile-amide intermediate.", "reasoning": "Formamide networks can access nitrile-containing intermediates relevant to amino acid synthesis; this step is included as a plausible bridge from HCN hydration chemistry to glycine precursors though exact structure/yield is less established (Saladino et al., 2012; speculative integration)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Surface hydrolytic conversion of activated glycine nitrile-amide to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry hydrolysis in mineral-rich pool"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile and amide hydrolysis furnishes the amino acid carboxylate/ammonium pair identified as glycine.", "reasoning": "Mineral-assisted hydrolysis of aminonitrile-type precursors to amino acids is broadly accepted in prebiotic chemistry and provides a direct route from activated nitrile-amide pools to glycine (Peltzer et al., 1984; Danger et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles promote nitrile hydration and completion to amino acid"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide and acid stages to yield glycine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile is the canonical completion step of Strecker chemistry to glycine and is strongly supported in prebiotic amino acid synthesis literature (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Surface reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing pool with NH3 and dissolved H2 equivalents"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylate forms an imine with ammonia followed by reduction to the \u03b1-amino acid glycine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is a direct and metabolically relevant path to amino acids. Glyoxylate is the C2 analogue that gives glycine, providing a route independent of Strecker chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2017; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic transamination of glyoxylate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated prebiotic pool or mineral interface"}, "mechanism": "Amino transfer from alanine to glyoxylate generates glycine and regenerates pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Transamination is a key network-connecting process that links hydrothermally generated alanine and pyruvate to glycine synthesis through glyoxylate, creating a plausible proto-metabolic loop even if uncatalyzed rates are modest (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Biochemical decarboxylation/oxidative shortening of pyruvate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-380K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling; speculative multi-step net conversion"}, "mechanism": "Net conversion invokes pyruvate decarboxylation to a C2 carbonyl followed by amination and oxidation-state adjustment to glycine.", "reasoning": "This is a speculative net step included to represent a proto-metabolic shortening route from pyruvate to glycine in geothermal pools. It is less directly evidenced than Strecker or glyoxylate amination routes but helps capture plausible network flexibility around \u03b1-keto acid chemistry (speculative integration informed by protometabolic carbonyl chemistry: Muchowska et al., 2019)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Strecker route from hydrothermal formaldehyde", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates formate and formaldehyde, which feed a surface Strecker synthesis to aminoacetonitrile followed by hydrolysis to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_0