dation transformation.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_014\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Support glyceraldehyde-to-glyoxylate conversion with a specific photochemical or mineral-mediated mechanism\",\n        \"Consider alternative routes from sugar chemistry to glycine precursors, such as glyoxal or aminodiol chemistry\",\n        \"Retain borate-assisted aldol chemistry but strengthen downstream oxidation logic\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.89,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.32,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.65,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"The transamination logic is strong: alanine and glyoxylate are a credible prebiotic amino transfer pair, and the biochemical step is one of the most plausible in the network. However, this branch inherits the weaknesses of direct pyruvate synthesis and pyruvate-to-glyoxylate conversion. With better upstream support, this could become one of the best pathways.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Keep the transamination endpoint but source glyoxylate from glycolaldehyde oxidation rather than pyruvate fragmentation\",\n        \"Use a more defensible pyruvate formation route or supply pyruvate from a separate network branch\",\n        \"Specify mineral or cofactor analogues enabling transamination in the biochemical stage\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.48,\n        \"rxn_022\": 0.12\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.27,\n      \"pathway_coherence