ents for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which is a significant compliance gap relative to the design constraints. Overall, this is a creative and well-connected synthesis network with partial target achievement, but it falls short of robust approval at the full-network level because too many branches depend on undersupported chemistry. The strongest subnetwork is the hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to surface glyoxylate to glycine route, followed by Strecker chemistry when HCN availability is assumed externally.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.88, "rxn_002": 0.52, "rxn_006": 0.22, "rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_019": 0.93}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.69, "pathway_coherence": 0.88, "environmental_progression": 0.84, "target_achievement": 0.94, "overall_confidence": 0.77, "feedback": "Conceptually strong canonical Strecker route with good hydrothermal-to-surface flow. The key weakness is the proposed generation of HCN directly from formaldehyde and ammonia, which is not a well-supported prebiotic transformation under stated surface conditions. If an exogenous or separately generated HCN source is assumed, the downstream Strecker and hydrolysis steps are among the most plausible routes to glycine in the network.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006"], "suggestions": ["Replace rxn_006 with a more plausible HCN source such as atmospheric/photochemical cyanide delivery or ferrocyanide/cyanosulfidic chemistry", "Clarify whether rxn_002 is intended as stepwise CO2 reduction via methanol-equivalent intermediates rather than direct formate-to-formaldehyde conversion", "Specify mineral agents for all hydrothermal and surface reactions"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.52, "rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_019": 0.93}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.78, "pathway_coherence": 0.83, "environmental_progr