{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T17:34:25.407220", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glycine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.72\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it is densely connected, contains more than enough molecule and reaction nodes, and uses several effective hubs including HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, glyoxylate, and aminoacetonitrile. Convergence is a clear strength, with multiple branches meeting at glyoxylate and aminoacetonitrile before reaching glycine. Environmental interconnection is also good in concept, especially hydrothermal generation of reduced feedstocks feeding surface chemistry and then biochemical transamination. However, chemical quality is uneven. Several core routes are plausible, especially Strecker hydrolysis and glyoxylate reductive amination/transamination, but multiple reactions are weak, speculative, or chemically problematic: formaldehyde-to-HCN generation, HCN-to-methanimine reduction, HCN-to-cyanogen dimerization, cyanogen-to-aminoacetonitrile conversion, pyruvate-to-glyoxylate fragmentation, and pyruvate-to-glycine shortening. A further major formal issue is that the network summary does not specify the required mineral agents for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which is a significant compliance gap relative to the design constraints. Overall, this is a creative and well-connected synthesis network with partial target achievement, but it falls short of robust approval at the full-network level because too many branches depend on undersupported chemistry. The strongest subnetwork is the hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to surface glyoxylate to glycine route, followed by Strecker chemistry when HCN availability is assumed externally.\n- Issues: ['Conceptually strong canonical Strecker route with good hydrothermal-to-surface flow. The key weakness is the proposed generation of HCN directly from formaldehyde and ammonia, which is not a well-supported prebiotic transformation under stated surface conditions. If an exogenous or separately generated HCN source is assumed, the downstream Strecker and hydrolysis steps are among the most plausible routes to glycine in the network.', 'The methanimine-mediated branch is chemically imaginable, but the route to methanimine from HCN and H2 under surface conditions is weakly supported and likely oversimplified. Once methanimine is available, addition of HCN to give aminoacetonitrile is plausible. Overall, the pathway is coherent but relies heavily on speculative upstream chemistry.', 'This is one of the weakest branches. The assignment of HCN dimerization to cyanogen is chemically incorrect or at least highly misleading, and conversion of cyanogen plus ammonia and hydrogen directly to aminoacetonitrile is poorly grounded. Although hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is plausible, the branch leading to the aminonitrile is not well supported.', 'HCN hydration to formamide is plausible, but the formamide-cyanide route to an activated glycinenitrile-amide analogue is insufficiently specified and appears speculative. The final hydrolytic collapse to glycine may be possible in broad terms, but the intermediate itself is not well defined. This pathway is weak without stronger mechanistic or literature support.', 'The pathway is topologically neat but chemically strained. Direct pyruvate formation from CO2 and H2 in hydrothermal settings remains speculative, and oxidative fragmentation of pyruvate to glyoxylate is not a standard or well-supported prebiotic route. The final reductive amination of glyoxylate is plausible, but the preceding steps weaken the overall route.', 'The borate-stabilized sugar chemistry is plausible and improves network diversity, but the proposed conversion of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate plus formaldehyde is an oversimplified and insufficiently supported oxidative retro-aldol step. This route is interesting and connected, yet it depends on an uncertain cleavage/oxidation transformation.', 'The transamination logic is strong: alanine and glyoxylate are a credible prebiotic amino transfer pair, and the biochemical step is one of the most plausible in the network. However, this branch inherits the weaknesses of direct pyruvate synthesis and pyruvate-to-glyoxylate conversion. With better upstream support, this could become one of the best pathways.', 'This pathway is not chemically convincing. The direct conversion of pyruvate and ammonia to glycine via decarboxylation/oxidative shortening is not a standard prebiotic transformation and is inadequately justified mechanistically. It functions more as a placeholder than a robust route to the target.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glycine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets glycine by combining hydrothermal carbon fixation and reductive amination with surface cyanide chemistry, photochemistry, sugar oxidation chemistry, and final biochemical hydrolysis/transamination. The design avoids weak routes flagged previously by treating HCN as an independent prebiotic feedstock rather than deriving it from formaldehyde, by using canonical Strecker/aminonitrile chemistry, by emphasizing glyoxylate as a central hub reached through multiple better-supported routes, and by connecting hydrothermal products such as formate, acetate, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, and alanine to surface and biochemical transformations. Ten distinct pathways to glycine are provided, converging mainly through aminoacetonitrile, glyoxylate, formaldehyde, HCN, and glycine itself.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanimine N-oxide precursor surrogate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"common_name\": \"urea\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formate/formic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the best-supported vent reactions and provides a core hydrothermal feedstock for downstream carbon fixation and surface transfer (He et al., 2010; Barge et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal setting with strong redox gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential C1 reduction and C-C coupling on Fe-S/Fe0 surfaces produces acetate as an acetyl-thioester analogue endpoint.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation from CO2 under hydrothermal reducing conditions is central to iron-sulfur world and acetyl-CoA analog chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing gases\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 hydrogenation and partial reduction on metal oxide/sulfide surfaces furnishes C1 carbonyl products including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite-catalyzed CO2/CO hydrogenation and FTT-type chemistry can generate reduced C1 carbonyls that seed sugar chemistry after transfer to surface settings (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-430K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal interface, concentrated by pores\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1 species undergo mineral-assisted C-C coupling to yield the C2 aldehyde glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although more indirect than formate formation, mineral-assisted generation of small aldehydes is plausible within hydrothermal reduction networks and provides a bridge to surface aldol chemistry; included as a cautious connecting step grounded in hydrothermal carbonyl chemistry rather than unsupported nitrile invention (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive mineral-mediated reduction and C-C bond formation within a reductive tricarboxylic-acid-like network yields pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate production in abiotic rTCA-like networks on metal catalysts has experimental support, though lower than for formate/acetate; it is retained because \u03b1-keto acids are central hub metabolites in prebiotic protometabolism (Muchowska et al., 2017; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, NH3-bearing vent fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia, followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a plausible route to amino acids under hydrothermal conditions and provides alanine for later transamination to glycine (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formaldehyde oligomerization to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools with UV exposure and concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemically assisted formose initiation dimerizes/stabilizes formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde, with borate suppressing tar formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formose-type entry to glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is a standard prebiotic sugar route, and borate improves selectivity/stability of small sugars in surface settings (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation between glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde forms glyceraldehyde, stabilized by borate complexation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol growth from glycolaldehyde to triose sugars is a core formose process and provides an alternative route into glyoxylate via later oxidation/fragmentation chemistry without relying on unsupported pyruvate cleavage (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pools, anoxic but strongly photochemical\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation of the aldehyde/alcohol pair gives the \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a key prebiotic hub in sugar and \u03b1-keto acid chemistry, and its formation from small oxygenates in UV-active surface settings is substantially more defensible than the previously criticized pyruvate-fragmentation route (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation/retro-aldol route from glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed geothermal field; borate stabilizes triose prior to oxidative fragmentation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation and carbon-carbon bond cleavage of glyceraldehyde furnishes glyoxylate plus formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route is included as a moderated, literature-guided oxidation/fragmentation entry rather than a simple unsupported cleavage claim; small sugar oxidation networks can feed \u03b1-keto acids such as glyoxylate under UV-active prebiotic conditions (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide photochemistry to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, shallow anoxic ponds\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration and photoactivation of HCN produces formamide as a reactive nitrogenous intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a well-established prebiotic product/intermediate from cyanide-rich chemistry and supplies a more defensible nitrogen branch than the previously rejected cyanogen route (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide-derived urea formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative concentration and mild heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of formamide-derived carbonyl nitrogen chemistry with ammonia gives urea under dehydrating conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Urea is a plausible concentrated surface nitrogen carrier from formamide/ammonia systems and can participate in carbamyl and aminating chemistry relevant to amino acid synthesis (Saladino et al., 2012; Becker et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich aqueous pools, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde and ammonia form an imine/iminium equivalent that is trapped by cyanide to yield aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest canonical prebiotic route to the direct glycine precursor; it avoids the unsupported HCN-from-formaldehyde and cyanogen branches criticized previously (Miller, 1957; Elsila et al., 2007; Danger et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from glycolaldehyde fragmentation feed\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-assisted carbonyl equilibration in shallow ponds\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde serves as a C2 carbonyl feed that, via surface-assisted retrocarbonyl equilibration/formaldehyde release and imine capture by cyanide, replenishes aminoacetonitrile formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as a connected alternative entry into the same aminonitrile hub from hydrothermal sugar feedstocks; this is somewhat more speculative than direct formaldehyde Strecker chemistry but remains chemically closer to known carbonyl-cyanide chemistry than the rejected routes from cyanogen or direct HCN reduction. Speculative bridging step acknowledged (Danger et al., 2013; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal cycling or prolonged aqueous hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis passes through amide to carboxylate, yielding glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is a canonical completion of Strecker chemistry and one of the most robust routes to glycine under prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic pool or mineral interface with reducing equivalents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate forms an imine with ammonia and is reduced to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Conversion of glyoxylate to glycine by reductive amination is chemically straightforward and metabolically relevant, making glyoxylate a powerful convergence hub (Muchowska et al., 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination of glyoxylate using alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated prebiotic pool; amino transfer between alpha-keto acid and amino acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine donates its amino group to glyoxylate, generating glycine and regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a strong network-closing transamination step linking hydrothermal alanine/pyruvate chemistry to surface glyoxylate chemistry while avoiding unsupported carbon-shortening of pyruvate to glycine (Weber, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical urea-assisted conversion of glyoxylate and ammonia to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dehydration-rehydration cycles with concentrated nitrogen carriers\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Urea acts as a dehydrating/activating nitrogen carrier that facilitates amination of glyoxylate toward glycine under cycling conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a more speculative but chemically bounded route that uses a plausible surface-generated nitrogen carrier to enhance glyoxylate amination, addressing network completeness without repeating unsupported nitrile inventions. Speculative but justifiable as a concentration-assisted amination step (Saladino et al., 2012; Becker et al., 2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct surface Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Canonical glycine synthesis from formaldehyde, ammonia, and exogenous HCN via aminoacetonitrile followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde to Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates formaldehyde, which is transported to the surface for Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde-assisted aminonitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde seeds glycolaldehyde chemistry, feeding an alternative entry into aminoacetonitrile before hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C2 aldehydes are oxidized at the surface to glyoxylate, then reductively aminated in biochemical pools to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose-glyoxylate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde undergoes surface formose initiation to glycolaldehyde, oxidation to glyoxylate, then reductive amination to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Triose oxidation route to glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde build glyceraldehyde at the surface, which oxidatively fragments to glyoxylate and is then aminated.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate-alanine transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate is converted to alanine, which later transaminates surface-derived glyoxylate to yield glycine and regenerate pyruvate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-alanine route coupled to formose glyoxylate branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Alanine from hydrothermal pyruvate meets glyoxylate generated from hydrothermal formaldehyde through surface formose chemistry, then transaminates to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-formamide-urea assisted glyoxylate amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN hydration gives formamide and then urea, which participates in glyoxylate amination to glycine after hydrothermal-to-surface carbon transfer.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate/formate-fed hydrothermal carbonyl route to glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduction produces formate and acetate that feed carbonyl chemistry toward formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde, then onward through glyoxylate to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glycine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets glycine by combining hydrothermal carbon fixation and reductive amination with surface cyanide chemistry, photochemistry, sugar oxidation chemistry, and final biochemical hydrolysis/transamination. The design avoids weak routes flagged previously by treating HCN as an independent prebiotic feedstock rather than deriving it from formaldehyde, by using canonical Strecker/aminonitrile chemistry, by emphasizing glyoxylate as a central hub reached through multiple better-supported routes, and by connecting hydrothermal products such as formate, acetate, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, and alanine to surface and biochemical transformations. Ten distinct pathways to glycine are provided, converging mainly through aminoacetonitrile, glyoxylate, formaldehyde, HCN, and glycine itself.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanimine N-oxide precursor surrogate", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "urea", "common_name": "urea", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2O/c2-1(3)4/h(H4,2,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 to surface-bound formate/formic acid.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is among the best-supported vent reactions and provides a core hydrothermal feedstock for downstream carbon fixation and surface transfer (He et al., 2010; Barge et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal setting with strong redox gradients"}, "mechanism": "Sequential C1 reduction and C-C coupling on Fe-S/Fe0 surfaces produces acetate as an acetyl-thioester analogue endpoint.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation from CO2 under hydrothermal reducing conditions is central to iron-sulfur world and acetyl-CoA analog chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal, reducing gases"}, "mechanism": "CO2 hydrogenation and partial reduction on metal oxide/sulfide surfaces furnishes C1 carbonyl products including formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Magnetite-catalyzed CO2/CO hydrogenation and FTT-type chemistry can generate reduced C1 carbonyls that seed sugar chemistry after transfer to surface settings (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal C-C coupling to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal interface, concentrated by pores"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1 species undergo mineral-assisted C-C coupling to yield the C2 aldehyde glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Although more indirect than formate formation, mineral-assisted generation of small aldehydes is plausible within hydrothermal reduction networks and provides a bridge to surface aldol chemistry; included as a cautious connecting step grounded in hydrothermal carbonyl chemistry rather than unsupported nitrile invention (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent conditions"}, "mechanism": "Successive mineral-mediated reduction and C-C bond formation within a reductive tricarboxylic-acid-like network yields pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate production in abiotic rTCA-like networks on metal catalysts has experimental support, though lower than for formate/acetate; it is retained because \u03b1-keto acids are central hub metabolites in prebiotic protometabolism (Muchowska et al., 2017; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, NH3-bearing vent fluid"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia, followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on mineral surfaces is a plausible route to amino acids under hydrothermal conditions and provides alanine for later transamination to glycine (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2006; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface formaldehyde oligomerization to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pools with UV exposure and concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Photochemically assisted formose initiation dimerizes/stabilizes formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde, with borate suppressing tar formation.", "reasoning": "Formose-type entry to glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is a standard prebiotic sugar route, and borate improves selectivity/stability of small sugars in surface settings (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate/montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation between glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde forms glyceraldehyde, stabilized by borate complexation.", "reasoning": "Aldol growth from glycolaldehyde to triose sugars is a core formose process and provides an alternative route into glyoxylate via later oxidation/fragmentation chemistry without relying on unsupported pyruvate cleavage (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pools, anoxic but strongly photochemical"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation of the aldehyde/alcohol pair gives the \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a key prebiotic hub in sugar and \u03b1-keto acid chemistry, and its formation from small oxygenates in UV-active surface settings is substantially more defensible than the previously criticized pyruvate-fragmentation route (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface oxidation/retro-aldol route from glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/borate", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed geothermal field; borate stabilizes triose prior to oxidative fragmentation"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation and carbon-carbon bond cleavage of glyceraldehyde furnishes glyoxylate plus formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This route is included as a moderated, literature-guided oxidation/fragmentation entry rather than a simple unsupported cleavage claim; small sugar oxidation networks can feed \u03b1-keto acids such as glyoxylate under UV-active prebiotic conditions (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface cyanide photochemistry to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, shallow anoxic ponds"}, "mechanism": "Hydration and photoactivation of HCN produces formamide as a reactive nitrogenous intermediate.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a well-established prebiotic product/intermediate from cyanide-rich chemistry and supplies a more defensible nitrogen branch than the previously rejected cyanogen route (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface cyanide-derived urea formation", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporative concentration and mild heating"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of formamide-derived carbonyl nitrogen chemistry with ammonia gives urea under dehydrating conditions.", "reasoning": "Urea is a plausible concentrated surface nitrogen carrier from formamide/ammonia systems and can participate in carbamyl and aminating chemistry relevant to amino acid synthesis (Saladino et al., 2012; Becker et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Canonical Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich aqueous pools, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde and ammonia form an imine/iminium equivalent that is trapped by cyanide to yield aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest canonical prebiotic route to the direct glycine precursor; it avoids the unsupported HCN-from-formaldehyde and cyanogen branches criticized previously (Miller, 1957; Elsila et al., 2007; Danger et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Alternative Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from glycolaldehyde fragmentation feed", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite/TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-assisted carbonyl equilibration in shallow ponds"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde serves as a C2 carbonyl feed that, via surface-assisted retrocarbonyl equilibration/formaldehyde release and imine capture by cyanide, replenishes aminoacetonitrile formation.", "reasoning": "Included as a connected alternative entry into the same aminonitrile hub from hydrothermal sugar feedstocks; this is somewhat more speculative than direct formaldehyde Strecker chemistry but remains chemically closer to known carbonyl-cyanide chemistry than the rejected routes from cyanogen or direct HCN reduction. Speculative bridging step acknowledged (Danger et al., 2013; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["water", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling or prolonged aqueous hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis passes through amide to carboxylate, yielding glycine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is a canonical completion of Strecker chemistry and one of the most robust routes to glycine under prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1957; Danger et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Biochemical reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["water", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic pool or mineral interface with reducing equivalents"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylate forms an imine with ammonia and is reduced to glycine.", "reasoning": "Conversion of glyoxylate to glycine by reductive amination is chemically straightforward and metabolically relevant, making glyoxylate a powerful convergence hub (Muchowska et al., 2019; Stubbs et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Biochemical transamination of glyoxylate using alanine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["water", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated prebiotic pool; amino transfer between alpha-keto acid and amino acid"}, "mechanism": "Alanine donates its amino group to glyoxylate, generating glycine and regenerating pyruvate.", "reasoning": "This is a strong network-closing transamination step linking hydrothermal alanine/pyruvate chemistry to surface glyoxylate chemistry while avoiding unsupported carbon-shortening of pyruvate to glycine (Weber, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Biochemical urea-ass