{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T17:37:24.500405", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glycine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.72\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it is densely connected, contains more than enough molecule and reaction nodes, and uses several effective hubs including HCN, formaldehyde, pyruvate, glyoxylate, and aminoacetonitrile. Convergence is a clear strength, with multiple branches meeting at glyoxylate and aminoacetonitrile before reaching glycine. Environmental interconnection is also good in concept, especially hydrothermal generation of reduced feedstocks feeding surface chemistry and then biochemical transamination. However, chemical quality is uneven. Several core routes are plausible, especially Strecker hydrolysis and glyoxylate reductive amination/transamination, but multiple reactions are weak, speculative, or chemically problematic: formaldehyde-to-HCN generation, HCN-to-methanimine reduction, HCN-to-cyanogen dimerization, cyanogen-to-aminoacetonitrile conversion, pyruvate-to-glyoxylate fragmentation, and pyruvate-to-glycine shortening. A further major formal issue is that the network summary does not specify the required mineral agents for hydrothermal and surface reactions, which is a significant compliance gap relative to the design constraints. Overall, this is a creative and well-connected synthesis network with partial target achievement, but it falls short of robust approval at the full-network level because too many branches depend on undersupported chemistry. The strongest subnetwork is the hydrothermal glycolaldehyde to surface glyoxylate to glycine route, followed by Strecker chemistry when HCN availability is assumed externally.\n- Issues: ['Conceptually strong canonical Strecker route with good hydrothermal-to-surface flow. The key weakness is the proposed generation of HCN directly from formaldehyde and ammonia, which is not a well-supported prebiotic transformation under stated surface conditions. If an exogenous or separately generated HCN source is assumed, the downstream Strecker and hydrolysis steps are among the most plausible routes to glycine in the network.', 'The methanimine-mediated branch is chemically imaginable, but the route to methanimine from HCN and H2 under surface conditions is weakly supported and likely oversimplified. Once methanimine is available, addition of HCN to give aminoacetonitrile is plausible. Overall, the pathway is coherent but relies heavily on speculative upstream chemistry.', 'This is one of the weakest branches. The assignment of HCN dimerization to cyanogen is chemically incorrect or at least highly misleading, and conversion of cyanogen plus ammonia and hydrogen directly to aminoacetonitrile is poorly grounded. Although hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine is plausible, the branch leading to the aminonitrile is not well supported.', 'HCN hydration to formamide is plausible, but the formamide-cyanide route to an activated glycinenitrile-amide analogue is insufficiently specified and appears speculative. The final hydrolytic collapse to glycine may be possible in broad terms, but the intermediate itself is not well defined. This pathway is weak without stronger mechanistic or literature support.', 'The pathway is topologically neat but chemically strained. Direct pyruvate formation from CO2 and H2 in hydrothermal settings remains speculative, and oxidative fragmentation of pyruvate to glyoxylate is not a standard or well-supported prebiotic route. The final reductive amination of glyoxylate is plausible, but the preceding steps weaken the overall route.', 'The borate-stabilized sugar chemistry is plausible and improves network diversity, but the proposed conversion of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate plus formaldehyde is an oversimplified and insufficiently supported oxidative retro-aldol step. This route is interesting and connected, yet it depends on an uncertain cleavage/oxidation transformation.', 'The transamination logic is strong: alanine and glyoxylate are a credible prebiotic amino transfer pair, and the biochemical step is one of the most plausible in the network. However, this branch inherits the weaknesses of direct pyruvate synthesis and pyruvate-to-glyoxylate conversion. With better upstream support, this could become one of the best pathways.', 'This pathway is not chemically convincing. The direct conversion of pyruvate and ammonia to glycine via decarboxylation/oxidative shortening is not a standard prebiotic transformation and is inadequately justified mechanistically. It functions more as a placeholder than a robust route to the target.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it has sufficient size, clear hub molecules, multiple convergence points, and good cross-environment connectivity from hydrothermal to surface to biochemical chemistry. The strongest parts are the Strecker/aminoacetonitrile route to glycine, the pyruvate-to-alanine branch, and the glyoxylate transamination/reductive amination endpoints. The weakest parts are several upstream transformations that are chemically underjustified, especially direct hydrothermal formaldehyde synthesis, hydrothermal formate/formaldehyde coupling to glycolaldehyde, the use of glycolaldehyde as a direct precursor to aminoacetonitrile, and the urea-assisted glycine route. Environmental interconnection is good in concept, but some pathway labels appear to overstate support. Overall, the network is acceptable as a broad exploratory synthesis map, but not all ten pathways are equally viable and the average confidence is pulled below approval threshold by several speculative reactions. A reduced network centered on P1, P7, and P8 would be substantially stronger.\n- Issues: ['Good environmental linkage from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface cyanide chemistry, but the key weakness is the proposed direct hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of formaldehyde from CO2 and H2. That step is substantially less established than formate or acetate production and lowers confidence in the otherwise strong Strecker branch.', 'This pathway is weakened by two issues: uncertain hydrothermal formaldehyde synthesis and a poorly justified alternative Strecker step from glycolaldehyde directly to aminoacetonitrile. Glycolaldehyde would more naturally lead to serine-like products or higher aminonitriles rather than glycine precursor aminoacetonitrile without fragmentation steps that are not represented.', 'The terminal glyoxylate reductive amination step is plausible and metabolically relevant, but the upstream formation of glycolaldehyde from formate and formaldehyde in hydrothermal settings is weakly supported, and oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate under explicitly anoxic prebiotic surface conditions needs better justification. The route is conceptually coherent but chemically uneven.', 'This is a reasonable surface-to-biochemical pathway in outline: formose chemistry can generate glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, and glyoxylate can feed glycine formation. However, the conversion of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate plus formaldehyde is too compressed and mechanistically underspecified, making the convergence into glyoxylate less convincing.', 'As with P5, the triose branch is attractive conceptually but depends on an insufficiently justified glyceraldehyde-to-glyoxylate transformation. The later glyoxylate amination step is plausible, but the route needs better mechanistic granularity to be compelling.', 'This is the weakest pathway. HCN to formamide under UV is plausible in broad terms, but the formamide-plus-ammonia to urea step is not a standard prebiotic route in this context, and the final urea-assisted conversion of glyoxylate and ammonia to glycine is highly speculative and not represented as a clear established mechanism. The pathway does not convincingly deliver glycine.', 'The hydrothermal front end is partly strong because formate and acetate production from CO2/H2 are plausible, but the claimed carbonyl coupling route toward glycolaldehyde remains the weak link. Once glyoxylate is available, conversion to glycine is credible. Overall this is a partially plausible but chemically uneven route.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glycine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets glycine by emphasizing chemically better-supported prebiotic routes and avoiding previously flagged weak steps such as direct formaldehyde-to-HCN generation, cyanogen-based aminoacetonitrile formation, pyruvate shortening to glycine, and underspecified pyruvate-to-glyoxylate fragmentation. The network uses externally plausible simple feedstocks (CO2, H2, NH3, HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, phosphate, water) and connects three environments. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1/C2 and keto-acid intermediates such as formate, acetate, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals. Surface chemistry uses HCN, aldehydes, borate-stabilized sugar chemistry, UV/TiO2 photochemistry, and phosphate minerals to generate aminoacetonitrile, glycolonitrile, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glyoxylate, and glycine. Biochemical/prebiotic chemistry then converts hydrothermal and surface intermediates through hydrolysis, reductive amination analogs, transamination, and peptide assembly. Ten pathways are represented as distinct valid routes to glycine, with strongest convergence at aminoacetonitrile, glycolonitrile, glyoxylate, and formaldehyde.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3O2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h2H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2HO3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxoacetate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3PO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(2-aminoacetyl)amino]acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycylglycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-1-3(7)6-2-4(8)9/h1-2,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents followed by release of formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is one of the best-supported hydrothermal entry points into prebiotic carbon fixation and is consistent with alkaline vent chemistry and iron-sulfur catalysis (He et al., 2010; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetate formation from CO2-derived C1 units\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline/subseafloor vent setting; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond formation among CO2-derived intermediates gives thioester-like acetyl equivalents that hydrolyze to acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation from CO2/H2 under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis is widely discussed as an analog of acetyl-CoA pathway chemistry and provides a plausible C2 feedstock (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from acetate and CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent-like conditions with dissolved Fe2+\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-promoted reductive carboxylation of C2 carbonyl/carboxylate chemistry yields alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is reported among products or proposed products of non-enzymatic CO2 fixation and reductive TCA-like chemistry on transition-metal minerals; while less direct than formate, it is a plausible hydrothermal hub (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic mineral surface; NH3 available\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia and is reduced on reactive iron/sulfide surfaces to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids is a central plausible prebiotic transformation, particularly on reduced iron-bearing mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation in anoxic hydrothermal fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal/mineral-assisted decarboxylation of pyruvate yields acetaldehyde and CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is a chemically straightforward carbonyl-generating step and is more plausible than direct shortening of pyruvate to glycine, which was avoided here (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pool; borate stabilizes sugar products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemically promoted carbonyl coupling of formaldehyde gives glycolaldehyde, which is stabilized in borate-containing aqueous surface settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Surface sugar-forming chemistry relies on formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as key feedstocks, and borate stabilization of early sugars/glycolaldehyde is widely invoked in prebiotic scenarios (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic or geothermal pool; wet-dry concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol addition of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde produces triose products, with borate stabilizing glyceraldehyde against decomposition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol/formose-type chemistry giving glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde under borate-rich surface conditions is plausible and experimentally explored in prebiotic sugar scenarios (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN addition to formaldehyde forming glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow aqueous pool; anoxic; intermittent UV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde gives the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile, concentrated on mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is canonical prebiotic chemistry. Glycolonitrile is a well-established early intermediate connecting cyanide chemistry to amino acids and sugars (Ferris & Hagan, 1984; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker formation of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporation-concentration cycles; mildly acidic to neutral microenvironments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form imine/methanimine equivalents, followed by cyanide addition to give aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker route to aminonitriles from aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN is one of the strongest and most classical prebiotic amino acid syntheses. Using formaldehyde directly avoids previously flagged unsupported upstream HCN-generation steps (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-rich drying pool; concentration by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Substitution/ammonolysis at the cyanohydrin-derived carbon center converts glycolonitrile into the corresponding aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile is a chemically sensible precursor to aminoacetonitrile under ammonia-rich cyanide chemistry, providing an alternative route to the same hub and improving convergence while remaining more grounded than previously criticized cyanogen branches. This step is plausible but less directly established than canonical Strecker synthesis, so it should be regarded as moderately supported (Matthews & Moser, 1967; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed pool; reversible cyanohydrin chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reversible cyanohydrin dissociation/hydrolysis regenerates glycolaldehyde and HCN from glycolonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin chemistry is reversible in aqueous environments, making glycolonitrile and glycolaldehyde an interconverting pair and creating realistic network density without inventing unsupported carbon skeleton changes (Ferris & Hagan, 1984).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photochemistry under anoxic conditions; radical oxidation using photogenerated oxidants rather than O2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation of the aldehyde alcohol functionality in glycolaldehyde gives the alpha-keto acid glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route is retained because glyoxylate is a metabolically relevant and chemically useful hub; here the oxidation is specified as anoxic UV/TiO2 photochemistry rather than vague aerobic oxidation, addressing prior criticism about underspecified oxidants (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Kitadai et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface oxidation of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-driven oxidative fragmentation in anoxic shallow pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidative C-C cleavage of glyceraldehyde yields glyoxylate and formaldehyde as a shorter-carbonyl fragment.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This transformation is more speculative than direct Strecker chemistry but is included as a constrained, explicitly photochemical fragmentation route to connect sugar chemistry back into glyoxylate and formaldehyde hubs. It addresses the need for environmental interconnection while acknowledging a literature gap (speculative; motivated by sugar photoredox fragmentation studies such as Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool; prolonged hydrolysis during thermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide/carboxamide-like intermediates to the alpha-amino acid glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the classical completion of the Strecker pathway and one of the most robust routes to glycine in prebiotic chemistry (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolysis of glycolonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH3-containing pool; multistep hydrolysis/amination sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolonitrile undergoes ammonolysis and nitrile hydrolysis through aminoacetonitrile or related amidic intermediates to furnish glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This represents a condensed but chemically sensible route from glycolonitrile to glycine in NH3-rich aqueous settings. It is less canonical than aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis but provides a second nitrile-based entry to the target and is preferable to previously criticized cyanogen-based proposals (moderately supported; Ferris & Hagan, 1984; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination of glyoxylate to glycine using alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool or mineral interface; repeated heating/cooling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to glyoxylate yields glycine and regenerates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination between alanine and glyoxylate is one of the strongest non-enzymatic biochemical-style routes in the network and was retained because it is chemically much more defensible than direct pyruvate-to-glycine shortening (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical reductive amination analog of glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic pool with dissolved Fe2+ and reducing equivalents transferred from hydrothermal system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate condenses with ammonia to an imine that is reduced to glycine under reducing prebiotic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct conversion of glyoxylate to glycine by reductive amination is metabolically and chemically plausible and provides a non-Strecker route to glycine. It is more conservative than the previously criticized pyruvate-fragmentation proposals (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical wet-dry condensation of glycine to glycylglycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative peptide bond formation between two glycine molecules yields the dipeptide glycylglycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Including downstream peptide condensation shows biochemical utility of the target and keeps glycine as a productive node rather than a dead end, consistent with wet-dry prebiotic peptide formation studies (Forsythe et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Strecker route from external formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct surface Strecker synthesis from formaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN to aminoacetonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin-first route from formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde first captures HCN to form glycolonitrile, which is then ammonolyzed to aminoacetonitrile and hydrolyzed to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct glycolonitrile-to-glycine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface glycolonitrile formed from formaldehyde and HCN proceeds through integrated ammonolysis/hydrolysis in prebiotic pools to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface carbonyl chemistry converts formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde and then to glyoxylate, which undergoes reductive amination to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Sugar-extension route to glyoxylate then glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde forms glycolaldehyde, then glyceraldehyde, which photochemically fragments to glyoxylate; glyoxylate is reductively aminated to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to alanine to glycine transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation gives pyruvate, which is aminated to alanine; alanine then transaminates glyoxylate in prebiotic pools to yield glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetate to pyruvate branch feeding transamination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction first produces formate and acetate hydrothermally; acetate is carboxylated to pyruvate, pyruvate to alanine, and alanine transfers amino group to glyoxylate to make glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate-decaboxylation branch to glyoxylate chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylates to acetaldehyde while surface carbonyl chemistry independently provides glyoxylate; the network converges on glyoxylate reductive amination to glycine, showing hydrothermal and surface coexistence of related carbonyl pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Reversible cyanohydrin loop reinforcing Strecker glycine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolonitrile reverts to glycolaldehyde and HCN, while formaldehyde-derived Strecker chemistry independently yields aminoacetonitrile that hydrolyzes to glycine; this pathway captures dynamic surface equilibration between cyanohydrin and Strecker branches.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical integrated route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate and acetate support pyruvate/alanine chemistry, while external surface HCN and formaldehyde generate aminoacetonitrile; glycine is then produced via aminonitrile hydrolysis as a complementary branch to transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glycine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets glycine by emphasizing chemically better-supported prebiotic routes and avoiding previously flagged weak steps such as direct formaldehyde-to-HCN generation, cyanogen-based aminoacetonitrile formation, pyruvate shortening to glycine, and underspecified pyruvate-to-glyoxylate fragmentation. The network uses externally plausible simple feedstocks (CO2, H2, NH3, HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, phosphate, water) and connects three environments. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1/C2 and keto-acid intermediates such as formate, acetate, pyruvate, and acetaldehyde on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide minerals. Surface chemistry uses HCN, aldehydes, borate-stabilized sugar chemistry, UV/TiO2 photochemistry, and phosphate minerals to generate aminoacetonitrile, glycolonitrile, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glyoxylate, and glycine. Biochemical/prebiotic chemistry then converts hydrothermal and surface intermediates through hydrolysis, reductive amination analogs, transamination, and peptide assembly. Ten pathways are represented as distinct valid routes to glycine, with strongest convergence at aminoacetonitrile, glycolonitrile, glyoxylate, and formaldehyde.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "methanoate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H3O2-", "iupac_name": "ethanoate", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h2H,3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2HO3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetate", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-aminoacetyl)amino]acetic acid", "common_name": "glycylglycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-1-3(7)6-2-4(8)9/h1-2,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents followed by release of formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals is one of the best-supported hydrothermal entry points into prebiotic carbon fixation and is consistent with alkaline vent chemistry and iron-sulfur catalysis (He et al., 2010; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal acetate formation from CO2-derived C1 units", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline/subseafloor vent setting; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond formation among CO2-derived intermediates gives thioester-like acetyl equivalents that hydrolyze to acetate.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation from CO2/H2 under hydrothermal Fe-S catalysis is widely discussed as an analog of acetyl-CoA pathway chemistry and provides a plausible C2 feedstock (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from acetate and CO2", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent-like conditions with dissolved Fe2+"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-promoted reductive carboxylation of C2 carbonyl/carboxylate chemistry yields alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is reported among products or proposed products of non-enzymatic CO2 fixation and reductive TCA-like chemistry on transition-metal minerals; while less direct than formate, it is a plausible hydrothermal hub (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic mineral surface; NH3 available"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia and is reduced on reactive iron/sulfide surfaces to alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids is a central plausible prebiotic transformation, particularly on reduced iron-bearing mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decarboxylation in anoxic hydrothermal fluid"}, "mechanism": "Thermal/mineral-assisted decarboxylation of pyruvate yields acetaldehyde and CO2.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is a chemically straightforward carbonyl-generating step and is more plausible than direct shortening of pyruvate to glycine, which was avoided here (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pool; borate stabilizes sugar products"}, "mechanism": "Photochemically promoted carbonyl coupling of formaldehyde gives glycolaldehyde, which is stabilized in borate-containing aqueous surface settings.", "reasoning": "Surface sugar-forming chemistry relies on formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as key feedstocks, and borate stabilization of early sugars/glycolaldehyde is widely invoked in prebiotic scenarios (Ricardo et al., 2004; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface aldol extension of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic or geothermal pool; wet-dry concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Aldol addition of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde produces triose products, with borate stabilizing glyceraldehyde against decomposition.", "reasoning": "Aldol/formose-type chemistry giving glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde under borate-rich surface conditions is plausible and experimentally explored in prebiotic sugar scenarios (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface HCN addition to formaldehyde forming glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow aqueous pool; anoxic; intermittent UV"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde gives the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile, concentrated on mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is canonical prebiotic chemistry. Glycolonitrile is a well-established early intermediate connecting cyanide chemistry to amino acids and sugars (Ferris & Hagan, 1984; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface Strecker formation of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporation-concentration cycles; mildly acidic to neutral microenvironments"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form imine/methanimine equivalents, followed by cyanide addition to give aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "The Strecker route to aminonitriles from aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN is one of the strongest and most classical prebiotic amino acid syntheses. Using formaldehyde directly avoids previously flagged unsupported upstream HCN-generation steps (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia-rich drying pool; concentration by evaporation"}, "mechanism": "Substitution/ammonolysis at the cyanohydrin-derived carbon center converts glycolonitrile into the corresponding aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile is a chemically sensible precursor to aminoacetonitrile under ammonia-rich cyanide chemistry, providing an alternative route to the same hub and improving convergence while remaining more grounded than previously criticized cyanogen branches. This step is plausible but less directly established than canonical Strecker synthesis, so it should be regarded as moderately supported (Matthews & Moser, 1967; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed pool; reversible cyanohydrin chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Reversible cyanohydrin dissociation/hydrolysis regenerates glycolaldehyde and HCN from glycolonitrile.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin chemistry is reversible in aqueous environments, making glycolonitrile and glycolaldehyde an interconverting pair and creating realistic network density without inventing unsupported carbon skeleton changes (Ferris & Hagan, 1984)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photochemistry under anoxic conditions; radical oxidation using photogenerated oxidants rather than O2"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation of the aldehyde alcohol functionality in glycolaldehyde gives the alpha-keto acid glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "This route is retained because glyoxylate is a metabolically relevant and chemically useful hub; here the oxidation is specified as anoxic UV/TiO2 photochemistry rather than vague aerobic oxidation, addressing prior criticism about underspecified oxidants (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Kitadai et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Surface oxidation of glyceraldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven oxidative fragmentation in anoxic shallow pool"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidative C-C cleavage of glyceraldehyde yields glyoxylate and formaldehyde as a shorter-carbonyl fragment.", "reasoning": "This transformation is more speculative than direct Strecker chemistry but is included as a constrained, explicitly photochemical fragmentation route to connect sugar chemistry back into glyoxylate and formaldehyde hubs. It addresses the need for environmental interconnection while acknowledging a literature gap (speculative; motivated by sugar photoredox fragmentation studies such as Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool; prolonged hydrolysis during thermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide/carboxamide-like intermediates to the alpha-amino acid glycine.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the classical completion of the Strecker pathway and one of the most robust routes to glycine in prebiotic chemistry (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical hydrolysis of glycolonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "NH3-containing pool; multistep hydrolysis/amination sequence"}, "mechanism": "Glycolonitrile undergoes ammonolysis and nitrile hydrolysis through aminoacetonitrile or related amidic intermediates to furnish glycine.", "reasoning": "This represents a condensed but chemically sensible route from glycolonitrile to glycine in NH3-rich aqueous settings. It is less canonical than aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis but provides a second nitrile-based entry to the target and is preferable to previously criticized cyanogen-based proposals (moderately supported; Ferris & Hagan, 1984; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Biochemical transamination of glyoxylate to glycine using alanine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_008"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated pool or mineral interface; repeated heating/cooling"}, "mechanism": "Amino transfer from alanine to glyoxylate yields glycine and regenerates pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Transamination between alanine and glyoxylate is one of the strongest non-enzymatic biochemical-style routes in the network and was retained because it is chemically much more defensible than direct pyruvate-to-glycine shortening (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Biochemical reductive amination analog of glyoxylate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic pool with dissolved Fe2+ and reducing equivalents transferred from hydrothermal system"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylate condenses with ammonia to an imine that is reduced to glycine under reducing prebiotic conditions.", "reasoning": "Direct conversion of glyoxylate to glycine by reductive amination is metabolically and chemically plausible and provides a non-Strecker route to glycine. It is more conservative than the previously criticized pyruvate-fragmentation proposals (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Biochemical wet-dry condensation of glycine to glycylglycine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative peptide bond formation between two glycine molecules yields the dipeptide glycylglycine.", "reasoning": "Including downstream peptide condensation shows biochemical utility of the target and keeps glycine as a productive node rather than a dead end, consistent with wet-dry prebiotic peptide formation studies (Forsythe et al., 2015)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Strecker route from external formaldehyde", "description": "Direct surface Strecker synthesis from formaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN to aminoacetonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_009", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanohydrin-first route from formaldehyde", "description": "Formaldehyde first captures HCN to form glycolonitrile, which is then ammonolyzed to aminoacetonitrile and hydrolyzed to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Direct glycolonitrile-to-glycine route", "description": "Surface glycolonitrile formed from formaldehyde and HCN proceeds through integrated ammonolysis/hydrolysis in prebiotic pools to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate to glycine", "description": "Surface carbonyl chemistry converts formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde and then to glyoxylate, which undergoes reductive amination to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_012", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Sugar-extension route to glyoxylate then glycine", "description": "Formaldehyde forms glycolaldehyde, then glyceraldehyde, which photochemically fragments to glyoxylate; glyoxylate is reductively aminated to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to alanine to glycine transamination route", "description": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation gives pyruvate, which is aminated to alanine; alanine then transaminates glyoxylate in prebiotic pools to yield glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_016", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal acetate to pyruvate branch feeding transamination", "description": "CO2 reduction first produces formate and acetate hydrothermally; acetate is carboxylated to pyruvate, pyruvate to alanine, and alanine transfers amino group to glyoxylate to make glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_016", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate-decaboxylation branch to glyoxylate chemistry", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylates to acetaldehyde while surface carbonyl chemistry independently provides glyoxylate; the network converges on glyoxylate reductive amination to glycine, showing hydrothermal and surface coexistence of related carbonyl pools.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Reversible cyanohydrin loop reinforcing Strecker glycine synthesis", "description": "Glycolonitrile reverts to glycolaldehyde and HCN, while formaldehyde-derived Strecker chemistry independently yields aminoacetonitrile that hydrolyzes to glycine; this pathway captures dynamic surface equilibration between cyanohydrin and Strecker branches.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_009", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_010", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical integrated route", "description": "Hydrothermal formate and acetate support pyruvate/alanine chemistry, while external surface HCN and formaldehyde generate aminoacetonitrile; glycine is then produced via aminonitrile hydrolysis as a complementary branch to transamination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_009", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_016", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_013", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_013", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_016", "rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 136818.6411857605, "success": true, "error_message": null}
